[1] Case updates
- Sat 15 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=9a337de507

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 14 Dec 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 529, with 481 confirmed and 48 probable cases. In total, there have been 311 deaths (263 confirmed and 48 probable) and 183 people recovered.
- 96 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 8 new confirmed cases, including 4 in Mabalako, 2 in Katwa, 1 in Kalunguta, and 1 in Komanda.
- 5 new confirmed case deaths, including 2 in Mabalako, 1 in Komanda, 1 in Katwa, and 1 in Beni. All are community deaths, except that in Beni.
- 1 new person recovered and discharged from the Ebola treatment center (ETC) of Beni.

News of the response
--------------------
- Bishop Sikuli Paluku, the bishop of the Butembo-Beni diocese, launched the "Family Without Ebola" campaign throughout the district of Butembo-Beni. This project is part of the "Ebola Pas Chez Moi" citizen campaign launched by Beni students last October [2018].
- In a statement issued Fri 14 Dec 2018, the bishop calls all Catholic faithful to protect themselves to protect their neighbors and their community. He particularly emphasized the importance of youth engagement in the Ebola response. Inspired by the passage in the 1st letter of St. Paul the Apostle to Timothy, chapter 4, verse 12, he reminded the youth that they are not only the future of the country. They are also the present. The bright future of the DRC will not happen without them.
- Bishop Sikuli Paluku also invited all the priests and other religious leaders to increase awareness during liturgical and paraliturgical celebrations. He regretted that, despite the efforts of the response teams, the epidemiological situation remained alarming and the epidemic continued to spread because of members of the population who refused to apply the hygienic prescriptions. He strongly condemned "the inhuman and cruel mischief" of all those who verbally or physically attacked the response teams and the pastoral agents involved in the outreach. He also denounced those who desecrated the graves by digging up people who had died of Ebola and some of whom ended up being infected. The bishop also announced that any family who would lend themselves to such acts will be punished by a suspension of pastoral and liturgical services, including the Eucharistic celebration and other sacraments, so as not to put the other faithful in danger.
- Religious leaders in the affected areas have been involved in sensitizing the population since the beginning of the epidemic. Bishop Sikuli Paluku has personally engaged in sensitizing the population by agreeing to be vaccinated and regularly denouncing the hostile behavior that has caused the spread of the epidemic.

Vaccination
----------
- Continued wide-belt vaccination (or ring plus) in Otomaber (in Komanda Health Zone) and Aloya (in Mabalako Health Zone).
- Continued immunization of primary care providers in the Goma Health Zone.
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 46 887 people have been vaccinated, including 18 855 in Beni [North Kivu], 8438 in Katwa [North Kivu], 5036 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 4606 in Butembo [North Kivu], 2178 in Kalunguta [North Kivu], and 1663 in Mandima [Ituri] (for the remaining vaccination figures, see the source URL).

- Fri 14 Dec 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://mailchi.mp/sante.gouv.cd/ebola_kivu_14dec

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 13 Dec 2018:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 521, with 473 confirmed and 48 probable cases. In total, there have been 306 deaths* (258 confirmed and 48 probable) and 182 people recovered.
- 97 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 3 new confirmed cases, including 1 in Beni, 1 in Kalunguta, and 1 in Komanda.
- 3 reports of confirmed cases from 12 Dec 2018, including 2 in Komanda and 1 in Beni, for which the laboratory results were released late in the evening.
- 2 new confirmed case deaths, including 1 in Kalunguta and 1 in Komanda. Both are community deaths.
- 3 new people recovered and discharged from the ETC in Beni.
*One hospital death occurred on 11 Dec 2018 in Beni and was added after database review and validation.

Vaccination
----------
- Continued wide-belt vaccination (or ring plus) in Otomaber (in Komanda Health Zone) and Aloya (in Mabalako Health Zone).
- Launch of the vaccination of frontline providers in the Goma Health Zone. A new vaccination ring was also opened in the community around Beni's contacts who had traveled to the South Mabanga district of Karisimbi, the 2nd health zone in Goma City. These people of Karisimbi are vaccinated as contacts.
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 46 047 people have been vaccinated, including 18 785 in Beni [North Kivu], 8298 in Katwa [North Kivu], 4985 in Mabalako [North Kivu], 4316 in Butembo [North Kivu], 2138 in Kalunguta [North Kivu], and 1663 in Mandima [Ituri] (for the remaining vaccination figures, see the source URL).

